Most of the people who are sexually abused early on don't remember it because it was a traumatic experience.

In short, your brain has 2 organs, the hippocampus and amygdala, which are responsable for networking the experience of the brain into narratives that have a property of congruence or that make sense. When a baby is first born it doesn't see the world in a 3 dimensional way, it see's the world in a 2d of shapes and colors until it starts to crawl, then they realize mom doesn't randomly disappear around the corner, she's just around the corner, and then they begin to take in awe of just how many corners there are.

You can't remember every single thing that's ever happened to you in your life in one moment, you have to scope the memory to just what's useful to your survival or the opportunities you have right now, which is the hippocampus's responsability. Most people don't remember learning to crawl because who they are now is a vastly different person than who they were at as a baby. You query your mind more with specific narratives as an adult (and do so along certain habitations) rather than with atomic sensations such as emotions, timeframes, or olifactory\tactile\auditory\visual sensations.

So in short, what you should be doing is asking yourself "When was the first time I was attracted to [fetish]", going back to that time, then tracing whatever feelings seem odd back to when they started happening. They can be attached to people, animals, objects, shapes, smells, tastes, etc. From there you can start sequencing events that occured around that time, ask parents\siblings\friends, and reverse engineering your past. Old photos, toys, diaries, etc can be triggers to memory.

I've had severe debilitating c-ptsd for most of my life and most people don't survive the shit I've been through, this has been a helluva process to go through and learn.

Most of the sadomasochistic stuff starts out as guilt\shame complexes.

On any given emotion wheel (google it), the base emotions (center of the wheel) are what you start developing early in childhood and as you socialize and go through development of identity and boundaries, the stuff on the outside comes into play as more narratives and connotation of those narratives develop. If you trace emotions and feelings back to the time where they were first felt, often the more coarse ones are from when you were younger. A place to start may be with an anhedonia test (tons of freebie ones online) and with start placing your emotions and feelings on emotion wheels while you diary to help clarify what you are feeling and fill in the narratives. Errikson and Paiget place some degree of emotional development in their models so combining those with an emotion wheel is helpful. In most childhood developmental models, guilt\shame comes before boundaries, so people who don't understand boundaries didn't make it past that stage.

So this may take some explination but if I do it right it'll be mind blowing for you.

When a baby is first born, they don't have a concept of 3d objects, everything to them is 2d shapes and colors. They know instinctually to follow momma's face, so over time they associate sound with the face, and then when they crawl they realize that when mom disappears around the corner, she's just around the corner, she hasn't disappeared off the ether. At some point they realize the world goes on and on ad seeminglg infinitum. In the same way, one day your ability to remember stuff switches on. You stop reacting to things like an animal through your amydala, and start using your hippocampus to remember and respond to stuff through narratives. Instead of crying when you call and there's a bit of pain, you analyze for a split second what just happened and if you are OK, comparing it to the past, do a self-diagnostic, then either get back up or cry depending on if you've gashed yourself good or not.

One of the things that happens is when toddlers begin to socialize, everyone to them is their parent. Children first develop a sense of self (where do you start and end, and what do all of those sensations mean), then a sense of identity (e.g. the game mineral, animal, vegitable, when you learn identity you objectify things into an object then apply classifications to the object), with these identities applying to both themselves and everything around them. As identity becomes robust and a child is socialized they begin to apply boundaires to the identities to both identify opportunities and to maintain safety. Finally you get personality which is where, when everything else is equal, how you approach a problems and opportunities.

Welcome, Anon, sit down, rest and have a bite. Want to tell us your story? Here some tips to survive the wasteland, add your own if you want.

STEP #1, HYGIENE AND HOME:
Brush your teeth twice a day, morning and evening. Scrub'em good with all the movements you can think of, front/behind. This will take somewhere around 2 minutes. Floss once a day.
Moisturize your face with a cream after washing your face in the morning.
Depending on how much you sweat shower every or every second day.
Get a haircut every 2 months. If you are balding just cut'em short, anything else looks shit and insecure about it.
If your clothes are ripped, stretched and discolored as shit, get some new ones. Basic, monotone, cheap shirts will do just fine. Again, depending on your sweat wear'em between 1 and 3 days, then change. If you got a pile of dirty rags wash it.

This brings us to your home. Doesn't matter if you live alone or with your parents, clean your dwelling once a week. Empty bottles and packages are to be thrown away immediately, instead of hoarded. It's no work if you do it this way. Used plates, glasses, etc., are to be washed off immediately after use. Again, if you do it like this, it's way less work than cleaning off a whole pile of them.
Changing bed sheets and vacuuming the place once a week.

A healthy mind lives in a clean body, living in a clean place. All that grime on yourself and around you poisons your mind. This regime gets rid of that without too much effort. You will also feel a sense of accomplishment, which boosts you for what comes next, LEAVING THE HOUSE

STEP #2, LEAVE HOUSE:
Go out every day. Do long walks of atleast 2 hours. Explore your city, your surroundings. Go into alleys you never walked before. Whenever you think, oh whats there or I never was there or anything similiat, thats where you go!
Do not ask yourself shit, like "whats the use? Its useless anyway, still feel like shit." Empty your mind, just wander.

STEP #3, SOCIALIZE:
I want you to greet people on your walks. Not some barely audible mumble, but a clear greeting. Establish eye contact, throw'em a good day coupled with a nod or a quick wave. I want your face to glow and your voice to echoe joy when you do this. Doesnt matter if its forced and unnatural at first, its training, if it came natural to you we wouldn't have to have this conversation.

After a few weeks or months of doing everything I told you, you should feel better about yourself. You wont be chad, fucking bitches left and right and going through life constantly happy, but at leaat you wont feel absolutely miserable for once. You may be able to pull off more intense forms of socializing now.

Get into the habit of doing smalltalk with strangers, like cashiers or the people you meet on walks. It doesn't matter that it's benign and trivial shit, just do it. Observe them, what they wear, their hair, makeup, tatoos, whatever and throw them a compliment, ask them where they got it from, what meaning it holds to them. When the convo naturally found its end, say your goodbye and go on your way.

STEP #4, GET A REAL HOBBY:
You should be prepared now, physically and mentally, to go out there and take the risk of trying new stuff, which will include meeting people doing the same stuff, but you are ready for that.

Here are things I can vouche for: Bouldering/climbing, martial arts, swimming, biking, skating, going to a chess/go/shogi/mahjong/etc center where you can watch, learn and play. If you like reading, go to a library instead of doing it at home. Generally, I advise you to engage mind and body. Try several physical activities and intellectual/creative ones.

At this point it should become a self perpetuating cycle. Keep challenging yourself, keep experiencing,exploring and learning new things.
Learn to "live in the moment". Dont question the use or meaning, do not rationalize, try to let the stimuli wash over you like a river

- Tried mushroom nearly 6 times, LSD-like for me, great.
- Tried cocaine, 10 to 15 times, good, power, confidence, great, but really too short (sniff).
- Tried MDMA, nearly 6 to 8 times (some pills, and powder); full love, energy; good.
- Tried "Speed" some times (called like that in France, it's just "amphetamine") : full of energy, all the night, very good (sniff).
- Tried some RC's : 4F-MPH, 3-FPM, 3-MABP
- Now I have buprenorphine from medical prescription, just because I wanted it (at the time it felt like heroin, and in my country it's 100% paid by Social Security, so I thought of it as "free heroin"; now I'm addicted to it, and I can't get off it (but I can't see myself doing without it anyway, it's my fuel, without it I do nothing)).

Drugs are fine as long as they are an occasional experience, not a habit.
I should mention that I have a job, and I'm a 37 years old frenchy.

There are many methods but pond liner would probably be the most straightforward for a moat. Finding old house construction methods is not hard if you look around.
I've recently been interested in water but not like a moat. I want to live on a small meadow surrounded by old forest on one side and some new forest on the other that I guide. Hedgerows will mark the borders and keep people out while giving bugs and small animals shelter where the forest can't. Anyway back to the water. I won't have a lawn, the area dedicated to my house will be moss, stone, and ground cover. Maybe porous pavers. Beneath it will be plastic skeletonized cubes. The plastic will support the weight of whatever happens in the yard but it will be a huge rainwater storage.
If you have specific ideas it is good to write them out and even start drawing. Get an idea of what plants, how much you'll grow, how you will preserve them, and which animals and how you will raise, process, and preserve them/their products. Really should pick a general area too since it depends on climate, temperature, sun hours, rainfall patterns, frosts, etc.. It's overwhelming but you just need to go in with a plan. From reading it's apparent most successful people started small and over many years built things up. Don't wait until you have everything planned and then build it all in one season. Start playing with things on paper and move it to irl when you're able.
